o a house identified by the sign of a salmon, but in some cases an occupational name for a salmon fisher.","German and French (Alsace and Lorraine): habitational name from Salm on the Mosel, or from Salm in Alsace."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Heinrich","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>heim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’.  See  Henry ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["back-formation from Yiddish  <b>Iserl</b>  (a metathesized form of Israel), the final <i>-l</i> having been taken as a hypocoristic ending."],"variants":[{"name":"Issur","meanings":["variant of   Iser ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Heinrich Ier VON SALM was born in 1105, in Gerolstein, Daun, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany. He had at least 1 daughter with Hadwide DE LUTZELBOURG. He died about 1170, in Senones, Vosges, Lorraine, France, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1105–about 1170":"1105–umbes 1170","1135–1195":"1135–1195","1162–1200":"1162–1200","1105–1170":"1105–1170","about 1162":"umbes 1162","1105":"1105","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1162":"1162","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","Senones, Vosges, Lorraine, France":"Senones, Vosges, Lorraine, Prantsusmaa","Mühlheim":"Mühlheim, Offenbach am Main, Kreis Offenbach, Hessen, Saksamaa","Gerolstein, Daun, Rheinland-Pfalz, Allemagne":"Gerolstein, Daun, Rheinland-Pfa